<dl id="n12208a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12208a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12208a"> 208(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> heels to sit on <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12208a"><li>FW 476.31 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n12208a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n12208a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12208a">MS BL 47482b-66</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:011 <a name="rA1yd" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rA1yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1yd.htm#n12208a">Draft: III&sect;3A.1+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Ce sont eux qui donnent la fortune <font color="green">[et]</font> sur aucun il ne pousse de poils. &mdash; Le pied, le talon et la langue. (Note. Le pied parce qu&apos;il transporte le commer&ccedil;ant dans ses voyages, le talon parce qu&apos;on s&apos;assied dessus au cours des visites faites aux personnages puissants, la langue parce que le succ&egrave;s va aux beaux parleurs.) <br><font color="green">[These are the ones who bring luck and they have no hair. The feet, the heel and the tongue. (Note: The feet because they transport the merchant on his travels, the heel because you sit on it when you visit important people, the tongue because it brings success to good speakers.)]</font> <small> Maurice Delafosse, <a name="LNEG" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LNEG"><cite title="source">L'&acirc;me n&egrave;gre</cite></a> (1922) 171 (Riddles)</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
